{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1150"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1150"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.38,0.1,0.3,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman is seen on the ward round one week following an elective right total hip replacement for osteoarthritis. She reports a two-day history of left-sided calf tightness and mild swelling. She has been mobilising with assistance and is undergoing daily physiotherapy, but her mobility remains limited due to pain. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well, with vital signs within normal limits. Her left calf is slightly swollen and mildly tender over the mid-calf, with no overlying skin changes. A lower limb ultrasound reveals an 8 cm thrombus in the peroneal vein. The remaining venous system is normal. Her estimated glomerular filtration rate is 80 mL/min/1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u226590).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compression stockings and repeat ultrasound in one to two weeks","Apixaban for six weeks","Warfarin for three months","Enoxaparin for three months","Apixaban for six months"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a symptomatic, provoked, distal deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the peroneal vein following recent orthopaedic surgery and a period of reduced mobility. \u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban for six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Current guidelines recommend anticoagulation for people with distal DVT unless there are contraindications (such as active bleeding). A duration of six weeks is sufficient for a provoked, distal DVT, and direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are preferred over warfarin due to ease of use and similar efficacy. After the first mention, DOAC is the accepted abbreviation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression stockings and repeat ultrasound in one to two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative for people at high risk of bleeding or who have declined anticoagulation. However, this patient is symptomatic, has a clear provoking factor, and has no contraindications to anticoagulation, so this is not the preferred option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin for three months\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. A longer duration of anticoagulation (three to six months) is recommended for patients with provoked proximal DVT or pulmonary embolism. For a provoked, distal DVT, a shorter duration of six weeks is sufficient. DOACs are also preferred over warfarin, given their ease of use without the need for monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin for three months\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary, as low-molecular-weight heparin is generally reserved for individuals with contraindications to oral agents or in specific populations, such as those who are pregnant. The duration is also longer than recommended for a provoked, distal DVT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban for six months\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate, as six months of anticoagulation is recommended for unprovoked or proximal DVT, not for a provoked, distal DVT. The duration should be six weeks in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the key considerations are the location (distal), the provoked nature (recent surgery and immobility), and the presence of symptoms, all of which support a six-week course of a DOAC.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Six weeks of anticoagulation is recommended for provoked, symptomatic distal DVT unless there are persistent provocating factors (e.g., active malignancy).","Ultrasound surveillance is an alternative to anticoagulation for distal DVT in patients at high risk of bleeding.","Direct oral anticoagulants are preferred over warfarin due to ease of use (e.g., no requirement for monitoring) and similar efficacy."],"references":["Singh K, Yakoub D, Giangola P, DeCicca M, Patel CA, Marzouk F, Giangola G. Early follow-up and treatment recommendations for isolated calf deep venous thrombosis. J Vasc Surg. 2012 Jan;55(1):136-40. doi: 10.1016/j.jvs.2011.07.088. Epub 2011 Oct 7. Erratum in: J Vasc Surg. 2012 Apr;55(4):1226. PMID: 21982332. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21982332/","Jackson CD, Cifu AS, Burroughs-Ray DC. Antithrombotic Therapy for Venous Thromboembolism. JAMA. 2022 Jun 7;327(21):2141-2142. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.7325. PMID: 35575779. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35575779/","Tran HA, Gibbs H, Merriman E, et al. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism [published correction appears in Med J Aust. 2019 Jul;211(2):94. doi: 10.5694/mja2.50260.] [published correction appears in Med J Aust. 2020 Feb;212(3):108. doi: 10.5694/mja2.50486.]. Med J Aust. 2019;210(5):227-235. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30739331/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1150"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T09:43:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T09:44:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1150"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"